## Migration: ASP.NET Web Forms → ASP.NET Core (.NET 8)

### Pattern Analysis

Your code has two patterns that rely on `Thread.Abort` internally:

| Pattern | Framework Behavior | Core Replacement |
|---------|-------------------|-----------------|
| `Response.End()` | Throws `ThreadAbortException` to halt execution | Return from the action method |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | Calls `Thread.Abort` to end response | Return `RedirectResult` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Swallows expected abort | Remove entirely — no abort exists |

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // btnExport_Click → Action method returning FileResult
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // No Response.Clear/Write/End needed — just return a result.
        // The framework handles Content-Type and headers.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv");
    }

    // btnRedirect_Click → Action method returning IActionResult
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAction()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Response.Redirect("/login", true) → return Redirect()
            // No Thread.Abort, no need for early return tricks.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No catch (ThreadAbortException) needed — it doesn't exist in .NET 8.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() { /* ... */ }
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

---

### Key Differences & Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Explanation |
|---------|-------------|
| **`Response.End()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | In .NET 8 there is no `Response.End()`. Return an `IActionResult` instead — the framework writes the response after your method returns. |
| **`Response.Redirect(url, true)` doesn't exist** | The `endResponse` parameter relied on `Thread.Abort`. In Core, `Redirect()` returns a result object — execution continues normally to the `return` statement. |
| **Removing `catch (ThreadAbortException)` isn't optional** | `ThreadAbortException` doesn't exist in the `System.Threading` namespace in .NET 8 targeting. Code referencing it won't compile. |
| **Don't write to `Response.Body` then return a result** | Pick one: either write directly to `HttpResponse` (advanced streaming), or return an `IActionResult`. Mixing both causes errors. |
| **`User.Identity` can be null** | In Core, `User.Identity` may be null if no authentication middleware is configured. Use null-conditional (`?.`) access. |

---

### For Long-Running Exports (Bonus)

If `GenerateReport()` is slow, use `HttpContext.RequestAborted` for cooperative cancellation:

```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> Export(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // ASP.NET Core auto-binds HttpContext.RequestAborted to this parameter
    var data = await GenerateReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    return File(System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data), "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```

This replaces the old pattern where `Response.End()` would abort in-flight work — now the client disconnecting signals cancellation cooperatively via the token.
